John Edward: Language skills for world citizens essential
Scotland’s independent schools continue to be distinguished by academic excellence. This continued in 2018 with further outstanding examination results and is only supported by individual and joint successes in the fields of sport, art, music and other community ventures.
With more than 30,000 students from all over Scotland, these schools, represented by the Scottish Council of Independent Schools (SCIS), strive to care for their students and their parents at the highest possible level.
Independent schools pursue the goal of preparing their students for further education and higher education, the profession of their choice and their place as world citizens.
As an educational sector that can design and implement a tailor-made curriculum, we see that modern languages are still popular and sought after in schools.
Nelson Mandela said: “If you speak to someone in a language he understands, you reach his head.
If you speak to him in his own language, you reach out to his heart."
This is an impressive reminder that we cannot rely only on English if we want to build relationships and trust with people from other countries.
The current audit results of this year are found to be at the top of the rankings of the independent schools.
A total of 68 percent of the students who learned foreign languages achieved the grade A during the higher examinations.
According to the data collected by 74 SCIS member schools, 72 percent of the students in Mandarin scored the grade A during the higher examinations, while 72 percent of the students who learned German achieved 69 percent of the students who learned French, and 63 percent of the students who learned Spanish also received the grade A.
This illustrates that independent schools in Scotland are supporting foreign languages as an important knowledge that children and young people will undoubtedly need in the future.
Languages are today regarded as elective subjects, as are STEM subjects (natural sciences, technology, engineering and mathematics) in the curriculums of independent schools and elsewhere.
According to a UK Commission for Employment and Skills survey in 2014, 17 percent of the reasons employers called for the problems of occupying positions were related to a lack of language skills.
As a result, language skills are increasingly required when it comes to preparing young people for their future profession.
Since more and more open places require languages, this knowledge is essential in a globalised world.
Independent of the chosen profession, young people who have learned a second language will have a real advantage through such a lifelong ability in the future.
To be able to communicate directly with people from other countries, multilingual people will automatically give an advantage to competitors.
According to a YouGov survey of more than 4,000 adults in the United Kingdom in 2013, 75 percent could not speak a foreign language well enough to conduct a conversation, and French was the only language spoken of a double-digit percentage (15 percent).
For this reason, it is important for the children of today that we now invest in language education.
Children who speak several languages, in particular languages of developing countries, will have better opportunities to find meaningful employment.
In Scotland, different languages are taught at all schools.
A number of schools will focus on the more classic modern languages, while other languages will be taught, which are considered the most important for the United Kingdom in 2020, such as Mandarin or Japanese.
Wherever your child's interests lie, in independent schools there will always be a number of languages with relevant specialised teachers to choose from.
Scottish independent schools are committed to creating a learning environment that prepares the children and equips them with the skills necessary for their success, regardless of the future.
At this point in a global economic environment, it cannot be denied that languages are still of fundamental importance for the future of the country. Therefore, this must be reflected in education.
In fact, modern languages should be regarded as 'international communication'.
Independent schools will continue to offer young people in Scotland this choice, diversity and excellence.
Il faut bien le faire.
John Edward is head of the Scottish Council of Independent Schools.
