A new course at Harvard University ensures that all students get more sleep this year in basic studies. This is a measure against the expanding macho culture of keeping awake with caffeine and learning all night long.
A scientist has found that students at the world's leading university are often unnecessary when it comes to taking care of themselves.
The course was designed by Charles Czeisler, professor of sleep medicine at Harvard Medical School and specialist at Brigham and Women's Hospital, and in his opinion is the first such course in the USA.
He was inspired to start the course after giving a lecture on the effects of sleep withdrawal on learning.
“At the end, a girl came to me and asked, ‘Why do I know about it only now, in my last year?’
According to her words, no one had ever told her how important sleep is. That surprised me," he told The Telegraph.
This year's first course explained to students how the basics of good sleeping habits contribute to academic and sporting performance and also improve general well-being.
Paul Barreira, professor of Psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and managing director of the university's health services, said that the university had decided to introduce the course after finding that students had been deprived of sleep during the week.
The one-hour course includes a number of interactive tasks.
In a section, the students see the picture of a room in a home and click on coffee cups, curtains, training shoes and books. They get information about the effect of caffeine and light as well as the effects of lack of sleep on the sporty performance and the importance of a sleep routine.
In another section, participants learn that long-term sleep withdrawal may increase the risk of heart attacks, strokes and cancer.
Then, using a map of the university grounds, they are encouraged to think about their daily routine with interactive symbols.
“We know that it will not change the behaviour of students immediately.
But we believe that they have the right to know this – just as you have the right to know how the decision to smoke affects your health," added Professor Czeisler.
The pride of "moving a night shift" was still widespread, he said, adding that modern technologies and the constantly growing pressure on students made sleep shortages a growing problem.
Sufficient sleep should be the "secret weapon" of all students against stress, exhaustion and anxiety, he said. Furthermore, weight gain could be avoided, as sleep withdrawal puts the brain into hunger mode so that they are constantly hungry.
Raymond So, a 19-year-old student from California who studies chemical and physical biology, helped Professor Czeisler to design the course. Last year he had completed one of his courses in Harvard in his first year.
