HIV/AIDS: China reports 14% increase in new cases
China has announced an increase of 14°% in the number of citizens living with HIV or AIDS.
According to health officials, more than 820,000 people are affected in the country.
About 40,000 new cases were reported in the second quarter of 2018 alone.
In contrast to the past, transmission took place in the vast majority of the new cases by sexual intercourse.
So far, HIV has spread rapidly in some parts of China as a result of infected blood transfusions.
However, the number of people thus infected with HIV has been reduced almost to zero, reported Chinese health officials at a conference in Yunnan Province.
However, in the annual comparison, the number of people living with HIV and AIDS has increased by 100,000 in China.
HIV transmission by sexual intercourse is an acute problem in China's LGBT community.
Homosexuality was decriminalized in China in 1997, but discrimination against LGBT community members is expected to be widespread.
Based on the conservative values of the country, studies have estimated that 70-90 % of men who have sex with men eventually marry women.
Many of the disease transmissions are due to insufficient protection in sexual intercourse in these relationships.
Since 2003, the Chinese government has been promising, among other things, general access to HIV drugs to address the problem.
