Why Beijing could benefit from the trade war between the USA and China
The opening ointments of the trade war between the USA and China were deafening. Although the battle is far from over, Beijing could benefit from a long-term grave between the countries, my experts.
Donald Trump, the U.S. President, fired the first warning shot at the beginning of the year when he charged with fines for major Chinese exports, including solar cells, steel and aluminium.
The most significant escalation took place this week with new fines on goods worth $200 billion, which effectively affects half of all goods imported from China into the USA.
Beijing struck back every time in the same way and recently raised fines of five to ten percent on American goods worth 60 billion dollars.
China has sworn to respond to any US measure and it is unlikely that the second largest economic power in the world will soon stumble.
However, a public intrusion towards the US would be far too derisive for China's President Xi Jinping.
Nevertheless, experts believe that if Beijing plays its cards well, China can benefit from the long-term effects of the trade war by reducing the mutual dependence of the two economies.
