Syria is 'ready' for the return of refugees, says the Foreign Minister
Syria says that it is ready for the voluntary return of refugees and asks for help to rebuild the country devastated by the war that has lasted for seven years.
In a speech to the General Assembly of the United Nations, Foreign Minister Walid al-Moualem stated that the situation in the country was improving.
"Today the situation on the ground is more stable and safer thanks to the progress made in the fight against terrorism," he said.
The government is rebuilding the areas destroyed by terrorists to restore normality.
All conditions were now given for the voluntary return of refugees to the country, which they had to leave due to terrorism and unilateral economic measures aimed at their everyday lives and livelihoods.
The UN estimates that over 5.5 million Syrians have left the country since the beginning of the war in 2011.
Another six million people still living in the country need humanitarian aid.
Al-Moualem said that the Syrian government welcomed aid in the reconstruction of the devastated country.
However, he stressed that it would not accept any conditions of assistance from countries that had supported the uprising.
