Update to the Red Tide: Concentrations in Pinellas, Manatee and Sarasota are decreasing
The latest report by the Florida Fish and Wildlife Commission shows a general decline in red Tide concentrations in parts of the Tampa Bay area.
According to the FWC, in the areas of the districts of Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Charlotte and Collier, more bleak flowering conditions are recorded, indicating declining concentrations.
A red algae flower extends over about 130 miles of coastline from the north of Pinellas to the south of the Lee district.
Some 10 miles off the coast of the Hillsborough district can be found, but fewer places compared to the previous week.
A red Tide was also observed in the district of Pasco.
In the last week, medium concentrations have been reported in or off the coast of the district of Pinella, low to high concentrations off the coast of Manatee County, background to high concentrations in or off the coast of Charlotte County, background to high concentrations in or off the coast of Lee District and low concentrations in the Collier District.
Respiratory complaints continue to be reported from the districts of Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Lee and Collier.
In the northwest of Florida, no new respiratory problems became known during the last week.
